@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@command{kitten} prints filesystem trees with entry metadata and optional
inline previews of regular text files.  It is intended for source-tree
inspection, review context, and bounded terminal snapshots.

Directories, regular files, symbolic links, and special files receive
distinct labels.  Symbolic links are never followed.  Names and link targets
are escaped before they are written to the terminal.

The default preview limit is 256 KiB per regular file.  Oversized and binary
files are labeled and skipped rather than treated as errors.

@node Invoking kitten
@chapter Invoking kitten

@example
kitten [OPTION]... [PATH]...
@end example

With no path, @command{kitten} inspects the current directory.  Options may
appear before or after path operands.  @option{--} ends option parsing and is
required before a path beginning with a hyphen.  A lone hyphen is an ordinary
path.

When exactly one directory is supplied, @command{kitten} verifies and enters
that directory, then displays the root as @file{./}.  Multiple operands are
printed as separate roots without changing the working directory.

Options for the same mode are applied from left to right.  For example, the
last @option{--ascii} or @option{--unicode} wins, and
@option{--content=auto} can re-enable previews after
@option{--no-content}.

@node Options
@chapter Options

@table @option
@item -m @var{bytes}
@itemx --max-bytes=@var{bytes}
Set the maximum preview size for one regular file.  The default is 256K.
@var{bytes} is an unsigned decimal number with an optional
case-insensitive K, M, or G suffix.  Suffixes use powers of 1024.

@item -L @var{depth}
@itemx --depth=@var{depth}
Limit directory descent to a non-negative depth.  Depth zero prints only the
root.  Depth one includes immediate children but does not enter them.

@item --exclude=@var{pattern}
Skip directory entries matching a POSIX @code{fnmatch} pattern.  The option
may be repeated.  Patterns are tested against the base name, traversal path,
and a traversal path with an initial @file{./} removed.

@item --no-content
Disable regular-file previews.

@item --content=auto
Enable the default preview policy.

@item --content=never
Disable regular-file previews.

@item --raw-content
Do not escape control data in preview text.  Tree prefixes and line
processing remain.  Entry names and symbolic-link targets are still escaped.

@item --dirs-only
Show and enter real directories only.  Symbolic links to directories are not
treated as directories.

@item -H
@itemx --human-readable
Format sizes in IEC units such as KiB and MiB.

@item -U
@itemx --unsorted
Use filesystem order instead of locale sorting.  This mode retains only one
pending child per open directory level.

@item --ascii
Draw trees with ASCII characters.

@item --unicode
Draw trees with Unicode box characters.

@item --summary
Print cumulative type, byte, skip, and error counters after traversal.

@item --language=auto
Select English or Russian messages from the active locale.

@item --language=en
Force English messages and labels.

@item --language=ru
Force Russian messages and labels.

@item --version
Print version and license information, then exit.

@item -h
@itemx --help
Print command-line help, then exit.

@item --
End option parsing.
@end table

Options requiring values accept either a separate operand or the long
@option{--name=value} form.  Short options cannot be grouped.  Numeric values
that overflow their implementation type are rejected.

@node Traversal
@chapter Traversal

@section Ordering

By default, visible names in each directory are collected and sorted with
@code{strcoll} under the active locale.  This gives locale-aware presentation
but stores the directory names in memory.

@option{--unsorted} uses the order returned by @code{readdir}.  One child path
is retained so the final tree branch can be drawn correctly.  Directory-entry
memory is therefore bounded apart from path length and recursive state.

@section Exclusions

Every @option{--exclude} pattern is matched against an entry's base name, full
traversal path, and path without an initial @file{./}.  A matching directory
is neither printed nor entered.  Patterns apply to discovered directory
entries, not root paths explicitly supplied as operands.

The syntax is POSIX @code{fnmatch}, not @file{.gitignore} syntax.
@command{kitten} adds no negation rules, repository discovery, or implicit
recursive wildcard behavior.

@section Depth and directory-only mode

The root has depth zero.  A depth limit controls descent; a directory at the
limit is still displayed.

@option{--dirs-only} displays entries for which @code{lstat} reports a real
directory.  Regular files, special files, and symbolic links are hidden and
counted as skipped.  A metadata failure remains visible so normal traversal
can report the error.

@section Symbolic links

Symbolic links are reported with their targets and never followed.  Targets
are read into dynamically grown buffers rather than fixed @code{PATH_MAX}
arrays.

@node File previews
@chapter File previews

Only regular files are candidates for previews.  The reading sequence is:

@enumerate
@item
Open the path without following its final symbolic link.
@item
Use @code{fstat} to confirm that type, device, and inode match the earlier
@code{lstat} result.
@item
Skip the file if its current metadata size exceeds the limit.
@item
Scan up to the limit for NUL bytes and read failures.
@item
Rewind and print the file line by line.
@end enumerate

A NUL byte classifies the file as binary.  Binary and oversized files are
skips, not errors.  Empty files receive an explicit label.

File changes can be observed as replacement, growth beyond the limit, read
failure, or truncation during the second pass.  The filesystem remains live;
the result is not a transactional snapshot.

Preview lines receive tree prefixes.  Trailing CR and LF bytes are removed,
then @command{kitten} writes its own newline.  @option{--raw-content} disables
escaping but does not produce a byte-for-byte copy.

The file is not loaded into one contiguous buffer.  The largest preview
allocation is bounded by the configured limit and the longest displayed line.

@node Output safety
@chapter Output safety

Entry names and symbolic-link targets are always escaped.  Newline, carriage
return, and tab use named escapes; backslashes are doubled; control and
invalid bytes use hexadecimal or Unicode escapes.

Default preview output preserves tabs and printable characters recognized by
the active locale.  ASCII controls, raw C1 bytes, invalid encoded bytes, and
multibyte control characters are escaped.  Backslashes in preview text are
preserved.

@option{--raw-content} disables preview escaping and should be used only with
trusted files.  It never changes name or link-target escaping.

Regular files and directories are initially opened with @code{O_NONBLOCK} and
@code{O_NOFOLLOW}.  The resulting descriptor must match the type, device, and
inode seen by @code{lstat}.  Non-blocking open prevents a path replaced by a
FIFO from hanging before type verification.  Confirmed regular files are
returned to blocking mode before stdio reads.

These checks detect common replacements but cannot prevent a file from
changing in place after it has been opened.

@node Summary and status
@chapter Summary and status

@option{--summary} reports:

@table @code
@item directories
Displayed real directories, including directory roots.
@item files
Displayed regular files.
@item symlinks
Displayed symbolic links.
@item special
Displayed entries of all other types.
@item bytes
The sum of observed regular-file metadata sizes, whether or not contents were
shown.
@item skipped
Entries filtered by options plus previews skipped as binary, oversized, grown,
or truncated.
@item errors
Observed metadata, open, read, allocation, and traversal failures.
@end table

The byte total saturates at @code{UINTMAX_MAX} and is marked on overflow.
Because @code{skipped} combines filtering and content decisions, it is not a
file count alone.

The exit statuses are:

@table @code
@item 0
Arguments were valid and traversal completed without an observed error.
@item 1
Arguments were invalid, a requested operation failed, or an output stream
could not be flushed.
@end table

Binary and oversized files do not make the status fail.  An error from any
root sets the final status to one while unrelated roots continue where
possible.

@node Localization
@chapter Localization

At startup, the process environment activates the C locale.  In automatic
mode, an @code{ru} message locale selects Russian labels and diagnostics;
other locales select English.  The normal @env{LC_ALL}, @env{LC_MESSAGES}, and
@env{LANG} precedence applies.

Option names and accepted values are always English.

Tree style is selected separately.  A codeset reported as UTF-8 or UTF8 uses
Unicode branches by default; other codesets use ASCII.

Before the main parse, @command{kitten} scans for a valid language option.
This allows a later language option to control diagnostics for an earlier
invalid option.

@node Examples
@chapter Examples

Inspect the current directory with previews:

@example
kitten
@end example

Print only the tree and metadata:

@example
kitten --no-content src
@end example

Limit depth and preview size:

@example
kitten -L 2 -m 64K path/to/project
@end example

Exclude repository noise and print totals:

@example
kitten --exclude=.git --exclude='*.o' --summary .
@end example

Use reproducible English and ASCII output:

@example
kitten --language=en --ascii --no-content .
@end example

Inspect a path beginning with a hyphen:

@example
kitten -- -example
@end example

@node Building and installation
@chapter Building and installation

Build the executable with:

@example
make
@end example

Run the bundled CLI integration checks with:

@example
make test
@end example

The Makefile uses the standard @env{CC}, @env{CPPFLAGS}, @env{CFLAGS},
@env{LDFLAGS}, and @env{LDLIBS} variables.  @env{WARNINGS} defaults to
@option{-Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic}; C99 mode is always selected.

Install the executable and manual page under @file{/usr/local}:

@example
make install
@end example

Select and stage another hierarchy with:

@example
make PREFIX=/usr DESTDIR="$pkgdir" install
@end example

Build and install this Info manual with:

@example
make info
make PREFIX=/usr DESTDIR="$pkgdir" install-info
@end example

@command{make clean} removes the executable and generated Info file.
@command{make uninstall} removes installed files from the selected prefix and
staging directory.

@node Portability
@chapter Portability

@command{kitten} targets C99 and POSIX.1-2008.  Native Windows APIs are not
supported.

Sorting and printable-character decisions depend on the active locale.
Binary detection is a NUL-byte heuristic; there is no MIME detection or
encoding conversion.  Exclusion patterns are shell patterns rather than VCS
ignore rules.  Directory recursion has no independent stack-depth guard, so
@option{-L} should be used for untrusted or exceptionally deep trees.

Metadata and contents may represent different moments in a concurrently
changing filesystem.  Output is designed for people and text capture; no JSON
or other machine-stable schema is provided.

The implementation avoids fixed @code{PATH_MAX} buffers and GNU-only
command-line parsing.

